# One story per pull request

Each pull request must address only one Jira story or one tightly related implementation objective. Changes should remain focused, isolated, and easy to review. Large multi-purpose pull requests should be avoided to reduce merge conflicts, improve traceability, simplify rollbacks, and enable parallel execution across agents.

Apply this rule when:

- creating pull requests
- implementing Jira stories
- decomposing implementation work
- reviewing pull request scope
- coordinating parallel agent execution
- validating implementation boundaries

## Agent behavior

- Before expanding scope: split extra goals into follow-up PRs or stories; keep the current PR aligned to a single ticket or one clearly named objective in the title/description.
- Prefer separate PRs for refactors, drive-by cleanups, or unrelated bugfixes unless the team explicitly accepts a bundled change with documented risk.

## Example

```text
❌ BAD — one PR: PROJ-123 auth fix + PROJ-456 report tweak + dependency major bump + formatting sweep

✅ GOOD — PR 1: PROJ-123 only (auth fix + its tests)
         PR 2: PROJ-456 only (report tweak + its tests)
         PR 3: dependency bump with release notes, or split by package if large
```
